Durban - Police have launched a manhunt for a gang of robbers who blew up a cash van and escaped with an undisclosed amount of cash on Monday night. 
 

 According to reports, the robbery took place on the Dundee/Nquthu Road in northern KwaZulu-Natal. 

 


 
 


 

 The Northern Coastal Courier reported that the men targeted the cash van, which was near the Buffalo River bridge. The gang is believed to have opened fire on the guards before blowing up the vehicle. 

 

 The suspects managed to grab the cash and flee. They were driving 
 two Toyota Hilux bakkies and an Audi.

 

 Last week, during the release of the national crime statistics, it was revealed that CIT robberies had increased drastically in the 2017/2018 financial year. 

In the 2016/2017 financial year, 152 CIT robberies were recorded in the country. The number increased sharply by 86 cases to 238 robberies in the 2017/2018 financial year.

 Earlier in the evening, three men were killed in a shooting with police on the N2 near Mandeni. It is alleged that police intercepted the men, who were on their way to commit a robbery when the shootout occurred.

 

 KZN police spokesperson, Lieutenant Colonel Thulani Zwane, said the police officers received a tip-off about the gang’s robbery plans. 
 Zwane added that three men were killed in the shootout. He added that no police officers were injured. 

 

